  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real concern, but I've seen it play out in my own life through the lens of my children's experiences. Growing up in a small town in Illinois, I never had the opportunity to engage deeply with science or math beyond what was taught in school. My parents both had only lower secondary education, so they couldn't help me with complex problems. But when I was in high school, I noticed how some of my classmates would become anxious when they were told they were 'not good at math'—it wasn't just about the subject, but about the fear of confirming a stereotype. My children, who are in college now, have faced similar challenges. One of my sons, for example, started to doubt himself in physics because he was told by a teacher that 'only certain people' were good at it. I've seen this pattern play out in my community, where people who are from underrepresented groups often feel they don't belong in STEM fields. As a retired teacher, I've seen how stereotype threat can be so subtle—it's not always about the stereotype itself, but how it affects a person's confidence and motivation. Should we address it? Absolutely. We need to create environments where everyone feels safe to try and make mistakes without fear of judgment. How? By starting early, through mentorship programs that connect students with role models who look like them, and by encouraging teachers to be aware of their own biases. I've volunteered with local science clubs for my children, and it's helped them feel more confident. In my community, we can do better by focusing on the individual, not the stereotype. It's about building trust and showing that everyone has the potential to succeed in STEM, regardless of their background.",
